           \pstart
           By the sheer force of his art, as it manifested itself in his works, in masterpiece
               after masterpiece, Dr. Arthur Schnitzler, a Jew,
               has won distinction in Vienna, the very hotbed of
               anti-semitism. He has surmounted many obstacles, combating prejudice calmly, yet with
               firm determination.\pend
           \pstart
           The following interview was had in the study of this brilliant writer in Vienna:\pend
           \pstart
           »What is becoming of Europe\oindex{Europa@\textbf{Europa}|pw}?« said Schnitzler. »The hate which has been intensified by the war is
               growing and spreading, and the most dreadful feature of it all is that people are
               talking of now wars in the near future.\pend
           \pstart
           \label{KT108-2v}\edtext{»It}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{»It}}}\Cendnote{\textnormal{In der Buchausgabe beginnt der Absatz mit: »\begin{otherlanguage}{english}›On August 1, 1914, – on the day of the
                        declaration of war – I wrote a letter to my brother\pwindex{Schnitzler, Julius@\textsc{Schnitzler, Julius} (13.\,7.\,1865 Wien – 29.\,6.\,1939 ebd.), \emph{Chirurg}|pwv} of which I should have been ashamed a
                        little later. I gave him my reasons why it was impossible that such a world
                        war could take place. It was a foolish letter in view of the events that
                        followed so rapidly, and that involved practically the whole world in the
                        war. But only now – after several years of so-called peace, we see clearly
                        that the war was really impossible.\end{otherlanguage}«}}}\label{KT108-2h} was the most brutal of all wars, it destroyed more values than
                  \label{K_I022-45v}\edtext{any previous war}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{any previous war}}}\Cendnote{\textnormal{In der Buchausgabe ist der Satz erweitert
                  um: »and it has left the world in a much worse condition than it was before
                     the war.«}}}\label{K_I022-45h}. We see chaos, poverty, ruination everywhere in Europe\oindex{Europa@\textbf{Europa}|pw}. And we see more hate than before the war.\pend
           \pagebreak[2] 
               {\centering\pstart[\vspace{0.35\baselineskip}]\noindent\leftskip=3em plus1fill\rightskip\leftskip
            Spread of Hate\pend[\vspace{0.15\baselineskip}]}\nopagebreak[4] \pstart
           \noindent{}»To check this spread of hate in various countries, it seems to me that it is urgent
               for intellectual leaders everywhere to create good will and a better understanding
               among the nations. A great campaign of education is essential in that direction.\pend
           \pstart
           »We have seen that Socialism has failed to meet the problems of war and peace
               effectively and has not exerted much of an influence either in the war or in the
               making of peace.\pend
           \pstart
           »We must realise, first of all, that man is the worst of all animals – the most cruel
               of them all. The difference between the human being and other animals is that the
               human being possesses such traits as joy at \label{T_I022-11v}\edtext{another’s}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{another’s}}}\Aendnote{\textnormal{anoher’s}}}\label{T_I022-11h} misfortune. Animals have no such terrible
               traits.\pend
           \pstart
           »We must also realise that while the human mind may be improved by education the
               human soul cannot be improved – for it cannot be changed. We may, therefore, hope
               that human beings will some day become wiser, but they cannot become better. Human
               beings are born egotists. They do not love one another unselfishly – they hate one
               another.\pend
           \pstart
           »All we may hope for is that the intellectual leaders may succeed in showing the
               people that they must stop wars because it would be best for them to have no wars –
               because they would benefit more from peace than from war.\pend
           \pagebreak[2] 
               {\centering\pstart[\vspace{0.35\baselineskip}]\noindent\leftskip=3em plus1fill\rightskip\leftskip
            Practical Pacificism \pend[\vspace{0.15\baselineskip}]}\nopagebreak[4] \pstart
           \noindent{}»Pacifism should not be sentimental. That is useless. Pacifists should not say that
               it is wrong to kill; that it is unethical to destroy human life; that it is immoral
               to commit such a crime; that other people suffer from such destruction, and that war
               is terrible on that account.\pend
           \pstart
           »Everybody knows that war is terrible; that it leaves dead and maimed in its wake;
               that it destroys property, and retards what is known as civilization. But such
               methods of reasoning, such arguments are of no avail. Human beings are not impressed
               by them. Human beings do not change their nature on that account.\pend
           \pstart
           »Instead of sentimental pacifism it is essential to convince them by education that
               peace would benefit them and save them – that in a roundabout way they themselves or
               their children may be the victims of war – the wounded, the mutilated, the dead.\pend
           \pagebreak[2] 
               {\centering\pstart[\vspace{0.35\baselineskip}]\noindent\leftskip=3em plus1fill\rightskip\leftskip
            The Quality of Love\pend[\vspace{0.15\baselineskip}]}\nopagebreak[4] \pstart
           \noindent{}»It is of very little value to preach love and the brotherhood of man, for it does
               not help. There are some people who believe that it is enough for them to preach or
               to listen to sermons on loving one’s neighbor as themselves – and that by this they
               have already discharged all their duties to their fellow-men.\pend
           \pstart
           »The quality of unselfish love is not inherent in human beings – and it is useless to
               demand of human beings to change that which cannot be changed. Besides, it is not
               necessary at all. I do not want people to love me. I do not want their kisses. I
               don’t think it necessary that there should be too much love among the nations.\pend
           \pstart
           »The important thing is that people should realize that they must not wrong one
               another – that they must not hurt or injure one another. The important thing is that
               people should have the opportunity to work, undisturbed, in peace; that they should
               not interfere with others; that they should not destroy others; that they should not
               rob others. They must learn to realise that war will affect them directly in some way
               or other just as they believe war would affect their enemy, their neighbor.\pend
           \pagebreak[2] 
               {\centering\pstart[\vspace{0.35\baselineskip}]\noindent\leftskip=3em plus1fill\rightskip\leftskip
            Rejoicing in Death\pend[\vspace{0.15\baselineskip}]}\nopagebreak[4] \pstart
           \noindent{}»Yesterday, while my daughter\pwindex{Schnitzler, Lili@\textsc{Schnitzler, Lili}, verh. \textsc{Cappellini} (13.\,9.\,1909 Wien – 26.\,7.\,1928 Venedig)|pwv}
               was packing to go to the country, we found a batch of old newspapers published during
               the war. I looked at the headlines. ›The Battle of – .‹{ }›We Captured 50,000 men. Tens of Thousands Slain.‹ And the
               jubilation over each victory! I remember how our people rejoiced when they heard that
               thousands of Russians\oindex{Russland@\textbf{Russland}|pw} were drowned in swamps.\pend
           \pstart
           »I was filled with terror as I recalled all this. Of course, the other side did
               exactly the same. They too, rejoiced when hundreds of thousands of our people were
               slaughtered. And I recalled with horror the indifference with which people afterwards
               read about those battles.\pend
           \pstart
           »When, for instance, they read that fifty thousand men had been slain, and on the
