           \pstart
           In a way this impression comes as a surprise. For there are in Schnitzler’s writing certain qualities of suavity which like the
               outward reserve of a well mannered person, are only the outcome of good artistic
               breeding, but which to superficial people belie the real temperament both of the
               artist and the man. Even a sympathetic and imaginative study of Schnitzler’s works will not always correct the error, and that is
               why I, as doubtless many others have done before me, came to him, expecting to find a
               personality cold, polished and courteous, a man of urbane scepticism, and gentle
               disillusionments, a temperamental agnostic, chastened of both anger and
               enthusiasm.\pend
           \pstart
           Of course all these things are precisely, what Schnitzler is not. The first thing
               that strikes one about him is \substVorne{}\textsuperscript{the}\substDazwischen{}a\substHinten{} most lov\substVorne{}\textsuperscript{\textcolor{gray}{×}\-\textcolor{gray}{×}}\substDazwischen{}able\substHinten{} warmth and impetuousnes\introOben{}s\introOben{}. He is both mentally and
               physically a young man, despite his years. His eye is clear, his complexion rosy, and
               his grey hair and beard are shot with streaks of blond. In his mental attitude Schnitzler is equally youthful. Whatever subject he
               touches, he is immediately on fire. His whole heart is in his talk, and he spends
               himself in it as recklessly as a boy of eighteen.{\pb}\pend
           \pstart
           I found Schnitzler in his little house in the
               suburbs of Vienna, in itself no mean achievement
               (finding him, I \label{T_I028-1v}\edtext{mean)}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{mean)}}}\Aendnote{\textnormal{mean}}}\label{T_I028-1h}\textcolor{gray}{,} for Schnitzler is one of the
               most sought after people in Europe\oindex{Europa@\textbf{Europa}|pw} and has more or
               less to barricade himself against intruders. Schnitzler had broken off some dictation to come down to me, and had so to
               speak to rub his eyes a little before he could launch out on the new topic. Also he
               seemed at first disinclined to grant the interview.\pend
           \pstart
           »I never give interviews,« he said. »All I have to say on the Jewish question is in
               my book ›Der Weg in’s Freie\pwindex{Schnitzler, Arthur@\textsc{Schnitzler, Arthur} (15.\,5.\,1862 Wien – 21.\,10.\,1931 ebd.), \emph{Schriftsteller, Mediziner}!Weg ins Freie. Roman1.\,1.\,1908–1.\,6.\,1908 – @\strich\emph{Der Weg ins Freie. Roman} {[}1\,1\,1908 – 1\,6\,1908{]}|pw}‹ I recommend – – –«\pend
           \pstart
           »Herr Doctor,« I said, »I have not read Der Weg in’s
                  Freie\pwindex{Schnitzler, Arthur@\textsc{Schnitzler, Arthur} (15.\,5.\,1862 Wien – 21.\,10.\,1931 ebd.), \emph{Schriftsteller, Mediziner}!Weg ins Freie. Roman1.\,1.\,1908–1.\,6.\,1908 – @\strich\emph{Der Weg ins Freie. Roman} {[}1\,1\,1908 – 1\,6\,1908{]}|pw} once but three times and it is to discuss that book I have come to
               you.« An extraordinarily sweet smile broke out over Schnitzler’s face.\pend
           \pstart
           »You are very flattering,« he said, and motioned me to a seat. And quite suddenly we
               were talking together\setul{-3pt}{0.3pt}\ul{ at 90 miles an hour}\resetul{}.\pend
           \pstart
           Talking to Schnitzler is a delightful business.
               The same sense of grace and form that is so perceptible in his books, is evident in
               his talk and bearing, despite his vehemence and ready enthusiasm. He has among other
               things a perfect genius for letting himself be interrupted. If he sees you have
               something to say he waves you off so to speak for a couple of sentences, and then
               gives you a fraction of a second to leap into the talk. It is like an obliging bus
               driver slowing down between the official stopping places.{\pb}\pend
           \pstart
           As one speaks to him, \substVorne{}\textsuperscript{one}\substDazwischen{}and\substHinten{} becomes conscious of this terrific depth and intensity of feeling of the
               continous mental rush going on with\introOben{}in\introOben{} the man\introOben{},\introOben{} one forms some conception of the degree of unrelenting
               discipline it must cost Schnitzler to have what he
               is namely one of the most polished and urbane writers in contemporary Europe\oindex{Europa@\textbf{Europa}|pw}. How easily that quick sensitivity, that
               overready response of the heart might have swamped his judgment and dimmed his taste!
               If Schnitzler had not been Schnitzler, he would one feels (not without a silent thanksgiving
               to Heaven for a calamity so nearly averted\introOben{})\introOben{}, have made one
               of those prolific emotional writers, who despite the presence of real talent never
               rise higher than the second rank in in the artistic hierarchy. \label{KT114-2v}\edtext{I remember thinking at the time that God hat
               originally intended Schnitzler for a sort of Upton Sinclair\pwindex{Sinclair, Upton@\textsc{Sinclair, Upton} (20.\,9.\,1878 Baltimore – 25.\,11.\,1968 Bound Brook), \emph{Schriftsteller}|pw}, and then at the last minute changed
               his mind.}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{I … mind.}}}\Cendnote{\textnormal{Dieser Satz durch eine Linie vom
                  Anfang des übernächsten Absatzes hierher bewegt.}}}\label{KT114-2h}\pend
           \pstart
           The truth is that there are two Schnitzlers. There
               is the emotional Schnitzler with the irresistible creative urge in him, and there is
               his mentor warder and familiar spirit, the critical Schnitzler, and it is by a collaboration of the two separate individuals
               that Schnitzler’s works come into being. This
               critical Schnitzler, I don’t mind telling you, is
               the devil of a fellow. He is persistent wakeful and utterly unrelenting. Even in his
               own domain, having no other object for his \introOben{}fury\introOben{}, he turns
               and lacerates himself.\pend
           \pstart
           »When I attempt any sort of critical or reflective writing,« said Schnitzler, »I am half strangled by my own parentheses.«\pend
           \pstart
           In other words Schnitzler is one of those not
               altogether enviable{\pb}{ }\label{T_I028-2v}\edtext{individuals whose}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{individuals whose}}}\Aendnote{\textnormal{whose}}}\label{T_I028-2h} judgments and critical faculty
               never have a holiday. It is a heavy price to pay, but in Schnitzler’s case the game is \label{T_I028-12v}\edtext{worth the candle}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{worth the candle}}}\Aendnote{\textnormal{worth candle}}}\label{T_I028-12h}.\pend
