           \pstart
           Complications greet the interviewer who would see Arthur Schnitzler, internationally known playwright and novelist, at his
               home in Vienna. For Herr Schnitzler, like most famous and much bothered men, is not at
               home to everybody and to guard against casual interruptions at his work has a silent
               telephone number. Although I have carried on a correspondence with him for a matter
               of 15 years or more, it was necessary for me to go through the formality of calling
               at his home, Sternwartestrasse 71\oindex{Wien@\textbf{Wien}!zz18XVIII., Waehring@\textbf{XVIII., Währing}!Sternwartestrasse@\textbf{Sternwartestraße}|pw}, inquiring for his
               telephone number and then making the telephonic introduction, which he requires, at
               an appointed time.\pend
           \pstart
           Yes, he would be glad to see me he said – sometime within the next day or two. The
               following morning Mr. Schnitzler called to say he
               would chat with me for an hour or so at 6 30 that evening.\pend
           \pstart
           The thing that struck me about the author of »Anatole\pwindex{Schnitzler, Arthur@\textsc{Schnitzler, Arthur} (15.\,5.\,1862 Wien – 21.\,10.\,1931 ebd.), \emph{Schriftsteller, Mediziner}!Anatol29.\,10.\,1892@\strich\emph{Anatol} {[}29.\,10.\,1892{]}|pw}\pwindex{Coschell, Moritz@\textsc{Coschell, Moritz}, geb. \textsc{M. Chocheles} (18.\,9.\,1872 Wien – 11.\,7.\,1943 ebd.), \emph{Maler}!Anatol29.\,10.\,1892@\strich\emph{Anatol} {[}Illustration, 29.\,10.\,1892{]}|pw}\pwindex{Hofmannsthal, Hugo von@\textsc{Hofmannsthal, Hugo von}, Pseud. \textsc{Loris, Theophil Morren} (1.\,2.\,1874 Wien – 15.\,7.\,1929 Rodaun), \emph{Schriftsteller}!Anatol29.\,10.\,1892@\strich\emph{Anatol} {[}Beitrag, 29.\,10.\,1892{]}|pw},« »Reigen\pwindex{Schnitzler, Arthur@\textsc{Schnitzler, Arthur} (15.\,5.\,1862 Wien – 21.\,10.\,1931 ebd.), \emph{Schriftsteller, Mediziner}!Reigen. Zehn Dialoge1900@\strich\emph{Reigen. Zehn Dialoge} {[}1900{]}|pw},« »\label{K_I087-12v}\edtext{Light o Love\pwindex{Schnitzler, Arthur@\textsc{Schnitzler, Arthur} (15.\,5.\,1862 Wien – 21.\,10.\,1931 ebd.), \emph{Schriftsteller, Mediziner}!Liebelei. Schauspiel in drei Akten9.\,10.\,1895@\strich\emph{Liebelei. Schauspiel in drei Akten} {[}9.\,10.\,1895{]}|pw}}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{Light o Love}}}\Cendnote{\textnormal{\emph{Liebelei}\pwindex{Schnitzler, Arthur@\textsc{Schnitzler, Arthur} (15.\,5.\,1862 Wien – 21.\,10.\,1931 ebd.), \emph{Schriftsteller, Mediziner}!Liebelei. Schauspiel in drei Akten9.\,10.\,1895@\strich\emph{Liebelei. Schauspiel in drei Akten} {[}9.\,10.\,1895{]}|pwk}}}}\label{K_I087-12h},« as he stepped from a room on the second floor of
               his carefully groomed villa, was his grayness. A gray beard that had grown beyond the
               well defined outlines of a Van Dyke\pwindex{Dyck, Anthonis van@\textsc{Dyck, Anthonis van} (22.\,3.\,1599 Antwerpen – 9.\,12.\,1641 London), \emph{Maler}|pw}; \label{K_I087-2v}\edtext{gray blue
               eyes}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{gray blue
               eyes}}}\Cendnote{\textnormal{$\triangleright$\myrangeref{L_I102_augenv}{L_I102_augenh}}}}\label{K_I087-2h} below gray brows and squinting lids: a gray mane combed from the right side of
               the massive head toward the left ear; a gray blue cutaway that seemed almost too
               tight for shoulders chunky rather than broad and indicative of a life at the desk
               rather than on football grounds.\pend
           \pstart
           I recalled his liking for gray from his letters – his \label{K_I087-14v}\edtext{stationery}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{stationery}}}\Cendnote{\textnormal{Schnitzlers Briefpapier
            hatte zeitweise einen bläulich-grauen Ton, doch ändert sich das über die Jahre und lässt sich keine
            Vorliebe für eine bestimmte Papierfarbe feststellen.}}}\label{K_I087-14h} was of that color. I
               was reminded at the same time that here was no longer the Schnitzler of the »Anatole\pwindex{Schnitzler, Arthur@\textsc{Schnitzler, Arthur} (15.\,5.\,1862 Wien – 21.\,10.\,1931 ebd.), \emph{Schriftsteller, Mediziner}!Anatol29.\,10.\,1892@\strich\emph{Anatol} {[}29.\,10.\,1892{]}|pw}\pwindex{Coschell, Moritz@\textsc{Coschell, Moritz}, geb. \textsc{M. Chocheles} (18.\,9.\,1872 Wien – 11.\,7.\,1943 ebd.), \emph{Maler}!Anatol29.\,10.\,1892@\strich\emph{Anatol} {[}Illustration, 29.\,10.\,1892{]}|pw}\pwindex{Hofmannsthal, Hugo von@\textsc{Hofmannsthal, Hugo von}, Pseud. \textsc{Loris, Theophil Morren} (1.\,2.\,1874 Wien – 15.\,7.\,1929 Rodaun), \emph{Schriftsteller}!Anatol29.\,10.\,1892@\strich\emph{Anatol} {[}Beitrag, 29.\,10.\,1892{]}|pw}«
               days but a man past 60, careworn and wincing under the reality of death, the same
               death with which he has toyed in so many of his plays and novels and which, a few
               months ago, took from him his beloved daughter.\pend
           \pstart
           Mr Schnitzler did not sit long at a time during
               our chat of two hours or so. He likes to stand or move about while he talks and this
               is his habit also when he is busy on a new novel or play. Mr Schnitzler stands there speaking with a voice of extremely
               musical timbre and with a precision of intonation and liveliness of tempo that bear
               no suggestion of the Viennese or Austrian »I should worry« attitude. He agreed with me that the
               much talked about geniality and social gracefulness of the Viennese are but surface elements, that the Viennese is spending too much of his time in the coffee house and that the
               traditional »Schlamperei« in public offices has grown rather than decreased in the 10
               years that Austria has been a republic. Holidays
               are declared on every pretext.\pend
           \pstart
           »We seem to have so much time here,« said Schnitzler, »but have we? Compared with Germany we are making slow progress in our reconstruction work. There are
               too many officials. It seems people must be employed somehow.«\pend
           \pstart
           I have observed that the only time when a Viennese
               has no time is when he has to make, or thinks he has to make, an electric train or
               street car. He will chase after it for a block and swing onto it with an athletic
               experience that is as remarkable as it is suicidal. Now police authorities are
               considering energetic steps to stop the nuisance which, clearly visible legends in
               all street cars inform you, is strictly prohibited by law.\pend
           \pstart
           Mr Schnitzler, by the way, considers railroad and
               electric train riding the most dangerous transportation hazards, more so than a
               trans-Atlantic boat trip. He would rather fly than float, and feels himself nowhere
               safer than when in an airship.\pend
           \pstart
           \sindex[question]{@!@}»I wouldn't mind a trip to America\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} but for the railroad distances. Once in America\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} I would want to see all. New
                  York alone wouldn't do. I have been approached several times by lecture tour
               managers but the financial reward offered does not warrant the effort.«\pend
           \pstart
           Which brought the conversation to the chronic emptiness of the Austrian pocketbook and the tremendous influence American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} financial and industrial supremacy is having
               upon all phases of life in Europe\oindex{Europa@\textbf{Europa}|pw} today.\pend
           \pstart
           »Anything and everything American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} is above par, in
               the public’s imagination as well as in the realities of the market,« said Schnitzler. »We imitate and adopt American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} clothes, American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} music,
                  American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} plays, American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} films, American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} traffic rules, American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} sports, American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} everything except American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} energy
               and success.«\pend
           \pstart
           Of American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} plays that are now »packing ’em in« over
               here Mr. Schnitzler had in mind »Broadway\pwindex{Abbott, George@\textsc{Abbott, George} (25.\,6.\,1887 Forestville – 31.\,1.\,1995 Miami), \emph{Schriftsteller, Regisseur, Schauspieler}!Broadway1926@\strich\emph{Broadway} {[}1926{]}|pw}\pwindex{Dunning, Philip@\textsc{Dunning, Philip} (11.\,12.\,1891 Meriden – 20.\,7.\,1969 Westport), \emph{Schriftsteller, Regisseur}!Broadway1926@\strich\emph{Broadway} {[}1926{]}|pw},« »Chicago\pwindex{Watkins, Maurine Dallas@\textsc{Watkins, Maurine Dallas} (27.\,7.\,1896 Louisville – 10.\,8.\,1969 Jacksonville), \emph{Drehbuchautorin, Reporterin}!Chicago1926@\strich\emph{Chicago} {[}1926{]}|pw},« »An American Tragedy\pwindex{Kearney, Patrick@\textsc{Kearney, Patrick} (9.\,10.\,1893 Columbus – 28.\,3.\,1933 New York City), \emph{Dramatiker}!American Tragedy11.\,10.\,1926@\strich\emph{An American Tragedy} {[}11.\,10.\,1926{]}|pw},« »The Trial of Mary Dugan\pwindex{Veiller, Bayard@\textsc{Veiller, Bayard} (2.\,1.\,1869 Brooklyn, NY – 16.\,1.\,1943 New York City), \emph{Schriftsteller, Dramatiker}!Trial of Mary Dugan1927@\strich\emph{The Trial of Mary Dugan} {[}1927{]}|pw}.«\pend
           \pstart
           »It is only seldom that I go to a theater,« the writer of world renowned plays
               declared. »I would go to concerts in years gone, my natural artistic inclination
               being decidedly more toward music than the stage. However, I am a keen frequenter of
               the kino (movie) as it permits one to come and go as one pleases and gives one many
               things that are not possible on the stage. I have seen quite a number of American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} films. There was a time when American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} pictures were poor, but that time is of the
               past.«\pend
           \pstart
           There are several persons whom Mr Schnitzler would
               like to meet should he come to America\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw}. One is a
                  \label{K_I087-1v}\edtext{publisher\pwindex{Seltzer, Thomas@\textsc{Seltzer, Thomas} (22.\,2.\,1875 Poltava – 11.\,9.\,1943 New York City), \emph{Übersetzer, Verleger}|pwv}}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{publisher}}}\Cendnote{\textnormal{\label{Label-K_I087-1v}\label{Label-K_I087-1h}Thomas Seltzer\pwindex{Seltzer, Thomas@\textsc{Seltzer, Thomas} (22.\,2.\,1875 Poltava – 11.\,9.\,1943 New York City), \emph{Übersetzer, Verleger}|pwk}, der 1922 das Werk
                  zuerst in einer teureren Ausgabe von 3.000 Stück, dann nachdem alle Exemplare
                  verkauft waren, im Folgejahr eine günstigere Ausgabe mit einer Auflage von 3–5.000
                  Stück publizierte, die nach kurzer Zeit um weitere 3.000 erweitert wurde. Bereits
                  für die erste Ausgabe beschränkte sich Seltzer\pwindex{Seltzer, Thomas@\textsc{Seltzer, Thomas} (22.\,2.\,1875 Poltava – 11.\,9.\,1943 New York City), \emph{Übersetzer, Verleger}|pwk}s Überweisung auf 200 Dollar Anzahlung und 500 Dollar Bezahlung, nur
                  ein Teil der zustehenden Summe, die Schnitzler
                  am 1. 6. 1923 in einem Brief an den Verleger mit 1.200
                  Dollar bezifferte. Auch nach Zahlung durch den Verlag musste Schnitzler mehrmals urgieren, um weitere Beträge zu erhalten.
                  In Folge engagierte den Rechtsanwalt Benjamin
                     Stern\pwindex{Stern, Benjamin Horace@\textsc{Stern, Benjamin Horace} (18.\,3.\,1874 New York City – 19.\,2.\,1950 ebd.), \emph{Rechtsanwalt}|pwk}, um zu seinem Recht zu kommen, doch noch 1926 musste
                     Schnitzler ausstehende Zahlungen einfordern.
                     Stern\pwindex{Stern, Benjamin Horace@\textsc{Stern, Benjamin Horace} (18.\,3.\,1874 New York City – 19.\,2.\,1950 ebd.), \emph{Rechtsanwalt}|pwk} antwortete entgegen der Darstellung
                  in diesem Interview sehr wohl, brachte aber die Sache nicht, wie von Schnitzler gewünscht, zu einem Abschluss.}}}\label{K_I087-1h}
               who, he said, paid him a pittance for the limited number edition of »Casanova’s Homecoming\pwindex{Schnitzler, Arthur@\textsc{Schnitzler, Arthur} (15.\,5.\,1862 Wien – 21.\,10.\,1931 ebd.), \emph{Schriftsteller, Mediziner}!Casanova s Homecoming1922@\strich\emph{Casanova’s Homecoming} {[}1922{]}|pw}\pwindex{Paul, Eden@\textsc{Paul, Eden}, geb. \textsc{Maurice Eden P.} (1.\,11.\,1865 Sturminster Marshall – 1.\,12.\,1944), \emph{Schriftsteller, Mediziner}!Casanova s Homecoming1922@\strich\emph{Casanova’s Homecoming} {[}Übersetzung, 1922{]}|pw}\pwindex{Paul, Cedar@\textsc{Paul, Cedar}, geb. \textsc{Gertrude Davenport} (1880 – 18.\,3.\,1972), \emph{Schriftstellerin}!Casanova s Homecoming1922@\strich\emph{Casanova’s Homecoming} {[}Übersetzung, 1922{]}|pw},« and the other a New Yorklawyer\pwindex{Stern, Benjamin Horace@\textsc{Stern, Benjamin Horace} (18.\,3.\,1874 New York City – 19.\,2.\,1950 ebd.), \emph{Rechtsanwalt}|pwv} whom he had engaged to
               prosecute the publisher but from whom he heard nothing after the first exchange of
               courtesies.\pend
           \pstart
           Schnitzler by the way, is \label{K_I087-4v}\edtext{still a practicing physician}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{still … physician}}}\Cendnote{\textnormal{Das ist auszuschließen, höchstens, dass er
                     sich im Familien- und Freundeskreis betätigte.}}}\label{K_I087-4h}, the
               profession which he followed exclusively before his success as a dramatist and
               novelist. Not a few of his plays are built around themes which have grown out of his
               medical experience. At the literary Burg theater\orgindex{Wien@\textbf{Wien}!zz01I., Innere Stadt@\textbf{I., Innere Stadt}!Burgtheater@Burgtheater|pw}\orgindex{Burgtheater@Burgtheater|pw}\orgindex{Burgtheater@Burgtheater|pw} in Vienna his most frequently played
