           \noindent{}\label{I061_L_crushedv}\label{I061_L_crushedh}That daughter\pwindex{Schnitzler, Lili@\textsc{Schnitzler, Lili}, verh. \textsc{Cappellini} (13.\,9.\,1909 Wien – 26.\,7.\,1928 Venedig)|pwv}, it will be
               remembered, had but recently married an Italian{ }\label{K_implied_14850v}\edtext{nobleman\pwindex{Cappellini, Arnoldo@\textsc{Cappellini, Arnoldo} (10.\,8.\,1889 Venedig – 8.\,5.\,1954 Rom)|pwv}}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{nobleman}}}\Cendnote{\textnormal{Arnoldo Cappellini\pwindex{Cappellini, Arnoldo@\textsc{Cappellini, Arnoldo} (10.\,8.\,1889 Venedig – 8.\,5.\,1954 Rom)|pwk}, der zwar (faschistischer) Offizier, aber
                  kein Adeliger war}}}\label{K_implied_14850h}, and a few weeks after her wedding she committed \label{K_I061-112v}\edtext{suicide}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{suicide}}}\Cendnote{\textnormal{Dies ist
                  nicht mit letzter Sicherheit feststellbar. Im Zuge eines Ehestreits spielte Lili Schnitzler\pwindex{Schnitzler, Lili@\textsc{Schnitzler, Lili}, verh. \textsc{Cappellini} (13.\,9.\,1909 Wien – 26.\,7.\,1928 Venedig)|pwk} am
                     26.\,7.\,1928 mit einem Revolver, doch ob der Schuss
                  absichtlich oder unabsichtlich gefeuert wurde, bleibt ungeklärt.}}}\label{K_I061-112h} in Venice. Dr. Schnitzler{ }\label{K_I061-44v}\edtext{chartered a special plane}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{chartered … plane}}}\Cendnote{\textnormal{Es stimmt, dass Schnitzler flog, aber mit der Linienmaschine.}}}\label{K_I061-44h} and flew
               to her bedside, but it was too late. The girl\pwindex{Schnitzler, Lili@\textsc{Schnitzler, Lili}, verh. \textsc{Cappellini} (13.\,9.\,1909 Wien – 26.\,7.\,1928 Venedig)|pwv} was dead. Broken in spirit, his face older and more tired,
               his eyes sadder, Schnitzler returned to Vienna and withdrew more and more deeply within
               himself. Of course, he still has his only son\pwindex{Schnitzler, Heinrich@\textsc{Schnitzler, Heinrich} (9.\,8.\,1902 Hinterbrühl – 12.\,7.\,1982 Wien), \emph{Regisseur, Schauspieler}|pwv}, a promising young actor, whom he sees nowadays from time to
               time. I cannot forget his sigh when he said: »It is hard to work in peace nowadays,
               free from crushing anxiety. {\dots} It is not like before the
               war.« And I sometimes wonder if old age and a consciousness of great work well done
               will at last bring him the healing gift of millennial peace.\pend
           \pstart
           Circumstances had, of course, been relentless toward him, as toward many others,
               during the spare and bitter war years and during the inflation of the Austrian crown and the German mark. His work was practically at a standstill. The royalties from
               the output of a lifetime – about twenty volumes of novels and plays in all – amounted
               to exactly {\$} 5. This was his income from the Fischer verlag\orgindex{S. Fischer Verlag@S. Fischer Verlag|pw}\orgindex{S. Fischer Verlag@S. Fischer Verlag|pw}\orgindex{S. Fischer Verlag@S. Fischer Verlag|pw}\orgindex{S. Fischer Verlag@S. Fischer Verlag|pw}, his German
               publishers. \pend
           \pstart
           Turkenschanz Park\oindex{Wien@\textbf{Wien}!zz18XVIII., Waehring@\textbf{XVIII., Währing}!Tuerkenschanzpark@\textbf{Türkenschanzpark}|pw}, near Schnitzler’s home, is one of the loveliest spots in Vienna. As the name indicates, the Turks, during their
               prolonged investment of the city, had built a fort there. \pend
           \pstart
           A short, stout man with curly brown hair and beard, profusely dusted with gray, came
               to meet me. His forehead was narrow, lined, his nose long and well modeled, his lips
               thick and full. But his most arresting feature was his eyes – they were deep-sunk and
               had penumbra; they where by no means cynical, as one might perhaps expect from some
               of his plays, but weary, self-effacing, asking little of people and things. He was
               well past sixty. \pend
