           \pstart
           After talking to Schnitzler for a half hour or so,
               I said to him: \pend
           \pstart
           »This is not an interview, Herr \label{TT147-1v}\edtext{Doktor}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{Doktor}}}\Aendnote{\textnormal{Docktor}}}\label{TT147-1h}.
               I shall not use it unless –« \pend
           \pstart
           »You may use whatever I say,« he replied, smiling. »But if you are wise you will wait
               several years. Interviewers have come to me from all over the world – and
               misrepresented me most horribly. I should like somebody who really knows me to write
               an interview. Now take this, for example« – and he strode over to his desk and drew
               out a newspaper clipping – »here is an \label{KT147-63v}\edtext{interview}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{interview}}}\Cendnote{\textnormal{nicht ermittelt}}}\label{KT147-63h} from
               a New York newspaper. It states, to begin with,
               that I am a man-about-town, that I attend all the redouts, that I am invariably to be
               seen at first nights and all important social functions; that I am to be seen at Sacher\oindex{Wien@\textbf{Wien}!zz01I., Innere Stadt@\textbf{I., Innere Stadt}!Hotel Sacher@\textbf{Hotel Sacher}|pw}’s every single night, drinking champagne or
               smoking an after-dinner cigar. This, as you know, is simply tissue of colorful lies.
               Of course I may now and then attend a first night – but then I am a dramatist. For me
               the main difference between the pre-war period and the present is this: Previously I
               had leisure and peace in which to work. Now, due to the state of social and political
               unrest, I am a good deal distracted, as any writer living in Vienna must be.«\pend
           \pstart
           \sindex[question]{@!@}As I rose to leave I turned to my host and
               asked: »Why is it, do you think, that your books have not had a steady sale in America\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw}?«\pend
           \pstart
            »I believe I am appreciated in America\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw},« he
               replied, »but so far I do not think I have had a fair chance. But the situation is
               about to change. The American\oindex{Amerika@\textbf{Amerika}|pw} public is waking up to
               the value of a psychological method in the delineation of character. Of course, it is
               easier for any audience to swallow light raillery or gay cynicism rather than ripe
               irony. Irony implies, as you know, a certain amount of intellectual sophistication.
               Perhaps this explains why my Vienna and Budapest colleagues are more successful on the New York stage than I am. {\dots} While wandering about Vienna,« he called
               after me as I was going out, »don’t forget to read Stifter\pwindex{Stifter, Adalbert@\textsc{Stifter, Adalbert} (23.\,10.\,1805 Horní Planá – 28.\,1.\,1868 Linz), \emph{Schriftsteller}|pw} and Grillparzer\pwindex{Grillparzer, Franz@\textsc{Grillparzer, Franz} (15.\,1.\,1791 Wien – 21.\,1.\,1872 ebd.), \emph{Schriftsteller, Beamter}|pw}.« \pend
           \pstart
           Shortly afterward I called on a well-known Viennese{ }\label{K_I061-1v}\edtext{lady\pwindex{?? Person@Nicht ermittelte Personen!?? [Salondame vor 1914]@\textsc{?? [Salondame vor 1914]}|pwv}}{\lemma{\textnormal{\emph{lady}}}\Cendnote{\textnormal{nicht identifiziert}}}\label{K_I061-1h} who had figured
               brilliantly in pre-war society. I inquired about the authenticity of Dr. Schnitzler’s characters. \pend
           \pstart
           »In Schnitzler,« I said, »there is always delicate
               charm, light amour and so on. Did the sex game, as his plays imply, once take up a
               good part of the lives of the Viennese?« \pend
           \pstart
           The lady\pwindex{?? Person@Nicht ermittelte Personen!?? [Salondame vor 1914]@\textsc{?? [Salondame vor 1914]}|pwv} laughed, her eyes
               suddenly grown youthful and gay. »Oh, Schnitzler
               is very, very clever,« she said, extending toward me a platter heaped up with rich
               pastry. »He’s profound, and, of course, almost any woman will recognize herself in
               one, at least, of his characters. I hear he’s been translated into every language.
               And he deserves to be, for he is universal – a great writer.« She\pwindex{?? Person@Nicht ermittelte Personen!?? [Salondame vor 1914]@\textsc{?? [Salondame vor 1914]}|pwv} paused. Her eyes glistened. »But,« she
